# RedwoodSDK: Ping / Pong JSX Route

## Background
RedwoodSDK (rwsdk) is a server-first React framework for the Cloudflare platform. It runs as a Vite plugin and lets you handle requests with `defineApp`, `render`, and `route` from the `rwsdk/worker` and `rwsdk/router` packages, where route handlers can return either a standard `Response` or JSX that is rendered to HTML on the server.

A baseline RedwoodSDK project has already been scaffolded at `/home/user/myproject`. Your job is to add a new HTTP route to the existing app that returns JSX and is rendered as a real HTML page.

## Requirements
- Add a new GET route at the path `/ping` to the existing RedwoodSDK app in `src/worker.tsx`.
- The `/ping` route must return a JSX element (not a raw `new Response(...)`), so that rwsdk renders it as a full HTML document via the `Document` shell.
- The returned JSX must contain the literal text `Pong` wrapped inside an HTML element (for example `<h1>Pong</h1>`).
- The existing routes (such as `/`) and the `Document` shell must continue to work; do not break the existing app.
- The project must still run under the standard dev server command (`npm run dev`) on the default Vite port `5173`.

## Implementation Hints
- Look at `src/worker.tsx` and observe how the existing app uses `defineApp`, `render`, and `route` from `rwsdk/worker` / `rwsdk/router`.
- Add a new `route("/ping", ...)` entry inside the same `render(Document, [...])` block so the new route also goes through the shared HTML document shell.
- Route handlers can return JSX directly; RedwoodSDK will render it to HTML on the server. No client-side hydration is required for this task.
- You do not need to add any new dependencies, change `wrangler.jsonc`, or modify the `Document` component.

## Acceptance Criteria
- Project path: `/home/user/myproject`
- Start command: `npm run dev`
- Port: `5173`
- API Endpoints / Routes:
  - `GET /ping`:
    - Returns HTTP status `200`.
    - Response `Content-Type` indicates HTML (for example `text/html`).
    - Response body is an HTML document whose body contains the literal text `Pong` wrapped in an HTML element (such as `<h1>Pong</h1>`, `<h2>Pong</h2>`, `<p>Pong</p>`, etc.). Plain text responses or bodies that contain only the bare string `Pong` without an enclosing HTML element are NOT acceptable.
  - `GET /` continues to respond with HTTP status `200` (the original route behavior must be preserved).


EOF
